07A915B498974670B7761D8E13EC62F7.description: Benchmark d: Child uses measurement vocabulary (e.g., length, weight, height) and comparative terminology (e.g., more, less, shorter, longer, heaviest, lightest), with teacher support and multiple experiences over time.

CD19BD0A292E4495A40C010CFD883D3D.description: Benchmark c: Child measures or compares the height of one or more objects using non-standard reference (e.g., pencils), with teacher support and multiple experiences over time.

1767C8271F414AFFA257E43D4F425C8B.description: Benchmark b: Child measures or compares the weight of one or more objects using non-standard reference (e.g., beans), with teacher support and multiple experiences over time.

courses, Simon Says, Mother May I?, hop scotch, giving simple directions).

Understands and can tell the difference between orientation terms (e.g., horizontal,
diagonal, vertical).

below, next to, beside, on top of, inside, outside).

Analyzes and constructs examples of simple symmetry and non-symmetry in two

process of how and why), with teacher support and multiple experiences over time.

3AC6A961104540C88BB9A042E49DED50.description: Sorts, orders, compares, and describes objects according characteristics or attribute(s) (seriation).

A583CA8980CD4F1EBC0B7B221895F364.description:

elements (e.g., red/blue, red/blue), with teacher support and multiple experiences over time.

91DFE08A6FA74089B236C03250D4A45C.description: Benchmark a: Child recognizes patterns and non-patterns.

6DD01BA683B9472BBC9819BFEEB8DD15.description: Understands characteristics of patterns and non-patterns and begins to reproduce them with at least two elements (e.g., red/blue, red/blue versus a non-pattern like a rainbow).

AC83DE6BB9B140F2B2B87F286B9AA99D.description:

with teacher support and multiple experiences over time.

D414293DDCBA47B68701DDD3CC840FB8.description:

3AA7BE1631C941A78A18876B63E54A0D.description:

0FF626100EAC48DAB3D1F2A6E5C03866.description:

nickname), not necessarily with full correct spelling or well-formed letters.

parts of words.

763B6487622A4D78B54958370E7626BE.description:

represent thoughts and ideas.

5A2CFA6D6A7A4E9C8AC91B815647546E.description:

artwork, captioning, labeling, creating lists, making notes).

4B4FABACB0B6473F887D4A7861ABA22D.description: Shows motivation to engage in written expression.

43AE81C214AE4C39B70B0F4364225B4E.description:

“What just happened?” “What might happen next?” “What would happen if…?” “What
was so silly about…?” “How would you feel if you…?).

C38CDEE065594891AC1D5CF3D120F089.description: Benchmark a: Child retells or reenacts a story after it is read aloud.

letters, can accurately identify the letter of the sound given).

letter, can accurately say its name).

32AEFCFFAE574ED0ABC6B6214A13F110.description:

group of letters, can accurately identify the letter that is named).

“at,” child can select the picture of the cat).

“candy” – “dy” = “can”).

2B9CBC79DAC34A028581916286635D51.description:
Benchmark c: Child deletes a word from a compound word (e.g., “starfish” – “star” =
“fish”).

360C645278B34111A8FDB4D49C9395DA.description:
Benchmark b: Child combines words to make a compound word (e.g., “foot” + “ball” =
“football”).

9424045B8568438181E952A508B99741.description: Benchmark a: Child can distinguish individual words within spoken phrases or sentences.

64EBEBB9ADAF4E44A3AD0887B1C34F8C.description: Benchmark c: Child asks to be read to or asks the meaning of written text.

CC26F15E72FB4D7694AFCFDEAB77EEA6.description:

environment.

520856B609D34BF0AAEF53A502259178.description:

and reading-related activities when given a choice, pretends to read to others).

Benchmark c: Child matches language to social and academic contexts (e.g., uses
volume appropriate to context, addresses adults more formally than he or she
addresses other children, and uses the more formal academic language of the
classroom).

62B0B6726D4B45879728B4589CD2ED89.description:
Benchmark b: Child demonstrates knowledge of nonverbal conversational rules (e.g.,
appropriate eye contact, appropriate facial expressions, maintaining a comfortable
distance in conversation).

CD0E1DC30E0D4D95A7B0AC9C23073592.description:
Benchmark a: Child demonstrates knowledge of verbal conversational rules (e.g.,
appropriately takes turns, does not interrupt, uses appropriate verbal expressions, and
uses appropriate intonation).

D19FD7A4E5C74DF99639E0222A42FE38.description: Uses appropriate language and style for context.

C4A5F8AEE3D24AF29AAA7177FCDF82BE.description:

himself or herself, requests assistance, answers questions by providing name and
address to a police officer or other appropriate adult).

0E8F60D02F2A40A39B2BA60E2B8BD2C2.description:

terminates conversations, or appropriately introduces new content.

522CA9051D444D5DAEEED14C4B63A467.description: Initiates, ask questions, and responds to adults and peers in a variety of settings.

530899616E0240A286FFEA79AC68D61E.description:
Benchmark a: Child demonstrates varied uses of language (e.g., requesting, commenting,
using manner words, problem-solving).

F49DBFF762AC4C478153CC250D44B347.description:
Uses language to express needs and feelings, share experiences, predict outcomes,
and resolve problems.

29267FB7A7E44198AFBBD6A9F9769C40.description:

93CC7E8BDDE94F2AB5F19B3FD7A6732B.description: Benchmark b: Child combines more than one idea using complex sentences.

831F8DFAB46A4EAE9C5C4753C2880620.description: Benchmark a: Child uses sentences with more than one phrase.

E1CC895DD7A74FC185C3E46145731FE9.description: Connects phrases and sentences to build ideas.

6DFE8FBCCB9449B69F83F35382D85342.description:

possessive pronouns, and subject-verb agreement.

DBAD9CAC3339499CAF03179661ACC3D0.description:
Benchmark a: Child typically uses complete sentences of four or more words, usually
with subject, verb, and object order.

E54CBE227A4F4738BF3E19D367A51884.description:
Uses age-appropriate grammar in conversations and increasingly complex phrases and
sentences.

6F71939E2F554677811F611BD189A9EE.description:
Benchmark c: Child uses a variety of word meaning relationships (e.g., part-whole,
object-function, object-location).

8C0F7ED9D09C485E8DA3FE1B9D41CCCB.description:
Benchmark b: Child uses category labels (e.g., fruit, vegetable, animal, transportation,
tools).

23D170AE45604CB9A774124486643FE5.description: Benchmark a: Child uses a large speaking vocabulary, adding new words weekly.

EDCE49B97FE543A7B86D7B52E2627CA3.description: Shows increased vocabulary to describe many objects, actions, and events.

F933198179814B68B40823ACBFB0DEF9.description:
Benchmark c: Child understands or knows the meaning of many thousands of words
including disciplinary words, (e.g., science, social studies, math, and literacy) many
more than he or she routinely uses (receptive language).

1FB03027A2E54C8A8406AE784F0628BA.description:

classroom (e.g., same and different, in front of and behind, next to, opposite, below).

Benchmark a: Child has age-appropriate vocabulary across many topic areas and
demonstrates a wide variety of words and their meanings within each area (e.g., world

520FB879D4A549A7B2AD4A2633875640.description: Shows an understanding of words and their meanings.

1A15F275BAD64B798F453D9EF9AD2C8C.description: Child’s speech is understood by both a familiar and an unfamiliar adult.

92D1BC9FC18546F0B0735999D91440C6.description: Speech is understood by both a familiar and an unfamiliar peer or adult.

9DC96A623B5B49A78EB15DC006CB68A6.description: Benchmark a: Child achieves mastery of two-step directions and usually follows three step directions, with teacher support and multiple experiences over time.

73413660E5B74BFFBB5F68C35800C031.description:
Benchmark a: Child shows understanding by asking and answering relevant questions,
adding comments relevant to the topic, and reacting appropriately to what is said.

9FBFE36F5FD84DC98A60E550A5C21FB3.description: LANGUAGE, COMMUNICATION, AND EMERGENT LITERACY STANDARDS

26B77973F5C24CFBBD9A174243B5A582.description: Develops an initial understanding of bullying, with support from familiar adults.

67527E8A01974A1C8FDFF0F4A2089444.description: Interacts with and develops positive relationship with peers.

5C9C0DE7761F4AA9B8A3039844D7E5E4.description: Shows increasing confidence in their own abilities.

F9F0CA6DCB12459486635517ED020BAF.description: Adapts to transitions with increasing independence.

1A6BBE9481E6481B8B14A1EB5B9D64E0.description: Begins to use materials with increasing care and safety.

46C47C62F1874C02B50F44C100CF2AF1.description: Follows simple rules, agreements, and familiar routines with teacher support.

29EB8FCEACBF452E99F1A62EA39B529C.description: Begins to recognize, then internally manage and regulate, the expression of emotions both positive and negative, with teacher support and multiple experiences over time.

B2E0CD23839B4A46ADF634A31DC8CE63.description: Demonstrates growing autonomy and independence, indicated by increasing self-care and willing participation in daily routines, when given a consistent and predictable environment.

DCB107A164334B36842181028C5FFE43.description: Shows initial signs of planning and learning from their experiences.

8B33E4C7AEEB4409B29EFCBD4A920152.description: Attends to tasks for a brief period and seeks help when needed.

D78368E9456A40D7ADE5E58AE3B44538.description: Shows curiosity and is eager to learn new things and have new experiences.

E9809EA86E074D7B987983D842612C0B.description: Shows beginning control of writing by using various drawing and art tools with increasing coordination.

5527385666C6463E92649E0916C3D353.description: Uses eye-hand coordination to perform fine motor tasks.

FCB26B3A2F28480DA511123319AB580B.description: Demonstrates increasing control of small motor muscles to perform simple tasks.

8A8643895A4B46DABD528C8D25C3CE94.description: Shows basic physical needs are met.

162B9AC779B84F249D3406D61157A8D1.description: Demonstrates self-control, interpersonal, and social skills in relation to mental health.

4FC87F68AF8D42158CA8B2A971BAC43C.description: Shows familiarity with health care providers in relation to health and wellness.

F214B4E767B7456A82E448EC0A82C92A.description: Demonstrates characteristics of good oral health and performs oral hygiene routines.

4BC538B0DACA4EEB8058D31D7CD4D55A.description: Demonstrates auditory ability to facilitate learning and healthy growth and development.

9610A05A1B6B4F77822D24874E4D6AB0.description: Shows visual abilities to facilitate learning and healthy growth and development.

F1F2BBE3539143288D3D4475704A7EAF.description: Shows characteristics of good health to facilitate learning.
